<li id="cite_note-97"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-97">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Syndicus, 39, 72–90</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-98"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-98">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Toynbee, 48–49. An exception in the Classical World were the <a href="Lycia" title="Lycia">Lycians</a> of <a href="Anatolia" title="Anatolia">Anatolia</a>. There are also the Egyptian mortuary-temples, where the object of worship was the deified royal person entombed, but Egyptian temples to the major gods contained no burials. For an extreme example, see <a href="Prohibition_of_death#In_antiquity" title="Prohibition of death">ancient Delos</a>.</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-99"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-99">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">It was allowed in times of plague however. See <a href="Cremation_in_the_Christian_World" title="Cremation in the Christian World">Cremation in the Christian World</a> for more details—the <a href="Orthodox_church" title="Orthodox church" class="mw-redirect">Orthodox churchs</a> still forbid cremation.</span></li>
